If one were to move the vertex of the above line slightly to the right, suddenly we would see two intersection points that were quite far away from each other. In other words, it doesn't feel like this one intersection point is the limit of some family of pairs of intersection points that come together in a limit. That would be a case against calling such a line tropically tangent. On the other hand, I can also see a case for calling such a line tangent.
